T1226_desc:
-Starting Position:
Stand with your feet together.
Keep your back naturally straight and tuck in your stomach and chest. Clasp your arms in front of your chest or cross your arms to maintain your balance.

-Actions:
Take a large step backward with one foot on one side, landing on your toes, dropping your hips, and squatting, with the knee of the front leg oriented in the same direction as the toes.
Squat down until the thigh of the front leg is parallel to the ground and slowly return to the starting position.

-Tip:
Inhale as you squat and exhale as you rise.
Stop training when you experience discomfort.
Tighten your core the entire time to avoid swaying your body.
You can carry a barbell on your back or hold a dumbbell kettlebell for weight training.

T1306_desc:
-Starting Position:
Lie on your back on a bench press bench, maintaining a stable position through your feet, hips, back, and head.
Hold dumbbells in your hands, palms facing each other, with the dumbbells spaced narrowly enough to touch, arms straight.

-Action:
Slowly lower the dumbbells, making sure they are spaced the same distance apart, until they are close to your chest.
Pause briefly and then power up to push the dumbbells back to the starting position.

-Tip:
Exhale as you push up and inhale as you return.
Stop training if you experience discomfort.

T1341_desc:
-Starting Position:
Sit in a seated position, maintaining postural stability through foot, hip, and back contact with the apparatus. Bend your elbows, keep your arms close to your body, and hold the handles of the apparatus with both hands.

-Action:
With three hairs, extend your elbows to press the handles downward. Pause briefly as arms straighten.
With three hairs force control the speed and slowly return to the starting position.

-Cue:
Exhale as you press down and exhale as you return.
Keep your elbows close to your body throughout the movement.
T1240_desc:
-Starting Position:
With hands and knees braced on the ground, slowly slide your knees out to the sides, keeping your thighs at a 90-degree angle to your body and your calves to your thighs.
Hook your feet back or press them into the ground and orient your toes in the same direction as your knees, avoiding inward or outward turning.
Head up, eyes flat in front of you, elbows on the ground.

-Action:
Push your body backward and feel the stretch in your inner thigh muscles.

-Tips:
Control the amplitude and stop the exercise if there is any discomfort.
T1223_desc:
-Starting Position:
Lie down on your stomach with your arms straight forward, legs straight, and your whole body relaxed against the floor with your forehead lightly tapping the ground.

-Action:
Simultaneously contract the muscles of the back, buttocks, and legs, lifting the upper body (chest, shoulders, and head), as well as the legs, up and off the ground at the same time. At the same time raise your arms upward as much as possible as well, keeping them straight.
During the movement, keep your neck naturally extended and do not tilt your head up or down excessively.
When the body reaches the highest point, pause briefly for 2 to 3 seconds and slowly return to the starting position.

Tips:
Exhale as you lift and inhale as you lower.
T1054_desc:
Starting Position:
Keep standing and reach down in order to hold a barbell with both hands (knees slightly bent).

Action:
Lift the barbell straight up without moving your back, knees or hips and lower it back after a short pause.

Tips:
Try to keep your back straight throughout. Only the arms should move.
T1290_desc:
-Starting Position:
Feet are 1.5-2 times shoulder width apart, toes are abducted about 45°-60°, and knees are oriented in the same direction as the toes.
Hold a barbell in both hands with a shoulder-width or slightly narrower grip, and keep your arms close to your inner thighs.
Hips down, back straight, core tight, shoulder blades aligned with barbell. The calves are close to vertical on the floor and the barbell is close to the shins.

-Action:
With your feet on the ground, push your hips forward and extend your hips to pull up the barbell.
Control your speed on the way down without the barbell touching the floor.

-Cue:
Exhale as you pull up and inhale as you lower down.
Choose foot spacing and range of motion based on flexibility.
T1001_desc:
Starting Position:
Maintain a fighting or defensive stance.

Action:
Use the fist, elbow, knee, foot and other parts to attack or defend the target.

Tips:
Pay attention to your center of gravity and your breathing rhythm.
T1105_desc:
Starting Position:
Pass a stretch strip under the bench, close to the side of the head, around the chest.Lie on your back on the bench with your chest out and stomach in, keeping your back straight.Hold one side of the elastic band in each hand and extend the arm up to shoulder width.

Action:
Then slowly lower your hands and bend your arms until your chest is stretched to the limit.Inhale as you descend.After a brief pause at the bottom, lift your arms up quickly with chest force until they are naturally straight.Exhale as you lift.

Tips:
In the process of two-handed descent, the force should not be fully discharged, and the force should be slowly reduced to improve the effectiveness of training.
T1276_desc:
-Starting Position:
Feet apart, shoulder-width apart, lean forward slightly, knees slightly bent, keep your body stable.
Lean forward, torso as parallel to the ground as possible, arms naturally hanging down, palms facing each other, thumbs forward.

-Action:
Raise and open your arms backward, pause briefly at the highest point, and hold your arms in an A-shape.
Slowly return to the starting position.

-Tips:
Exhale as you lift and inhale as you lower.
Stop the exercise if you experience discomfort.

T1057_desc:
Starting Position:
Lie on your stomach on the back extender with your ankle against the pad and adjust the top pad so that your upper thighs can lean on the pad and your waist is unrestrained when bending.
Keep your body straight with your arms crossed in front of your chest or behind your head.

Action:
Slowly bend forward, pressing as hard as you can until you can't, keeping your back straight and exhaling as you do so.After a short pause, use the strength of your lower back to slowly lift your body back to the Starting Position while inhaling.

Tips:
Keep your balance during the exercise and keep your back unbent.

T1381_desc:
-Starting Position:
Lie prone on a bench with your arms wrapped around the bench to maintain body stability.
With calves and thighs perpendicular and legs open, support the barbell bar with the balls of your feet.

-Action:
Contract your hips and power up to push the barbell bar upward. Pause briefly after reaching maximum amplitude.
Power up to control your speed and slowly return to the starting position.

-Tip:
Exhale on the upward thrust and exhale on the return.
Control the range of motion and weight to reduce the risk of injury.
Stop training if you feel discomfort during the movement.

T1004_desc:
Starting Position:
Lie prone on the floor, body fully extended, hands in a medium grip Position with only your hands and feet touching the floor.

Action:
Push yourself up by extending your arms and lower yourself back down after a short pause.Repeat to recommended number of times.

Tips:
Breathe out while pushing yourself up and breathe in while lowering yourself down.
T1175_desc:
Starting Position:
Stand still and let your arms drop.

Action:
Alternate your feet back and forth. Bend your knees slightly during the process. Keep the rhythm.

Tip:
Keep your balance and pace.
S10037: Your personal information will be used to calculate your physical fitness data during training.
T1097_desc:
Starting Position:
In a standing Position, hold a medicine ball in both hands, knees slightly bent, feet shoulder-width apart.

Action:
Lift your arms up, lift the ball over your head, and hit the ground in front of you.Wait for the ball to bounce, with both hands to catch the ball.

Tips:
The training process emphasizes the training of explosive force.
S10033: Do you want to log out?
S10031: Incorrect account or password, please re-enter
T1014_desc:
Starting Position:
Stand in front of a box with feet shoulder width apart, with legs slightly bent.

Action:
Use your arms and jump on to the box. Land softly with feet straight ahead and knees over feet. Step down and repeat as quickly as can be controlled.

Tips:
Use a box or step that is a suitable height for your fitness level.
T1360_desc:
-Starting Position:
Hang from the hang point with your hands, palms facing forward.

-Action:
Pull yourself upward with both hands until the height of your chin reaches the height of your palms and lower yourself after a brief pause.

-Tip:
You can adjust the difficulty of the exercise by adjusting the spacing of the hanging points and the number of hanging fingers.
Inhale as you raise yourself and exhale as you lower yourself.
C2002: An error occurred, please try again later.
C2001: Sorry,the page you want to visit does not exist.
T1148_desc:
Starting Position:
Hold the push-up position on the mat and keep your body straight.

Action:
Bend one arm, support the ground with the forearm, then repeat with the other arm, pause briefly and return to the push-up position in the same order.Repeat until recommended number of times.

Tip:
Keep your balance and keep your body straight during the exercise.
S10076:
The First Beta Rock Climbing Route Database!
Download this resource pack to enable quick and convenient route search and recording features on your smartwatch.

Supported Regions:
United States: California, Colorado, Nevada
Popular Areas: Yosemite National Park, Lover's Leap, Lake Tahoe, Eldorado Canyon State Park, Joshua Tree National Park, Red Rocks
China: Yangshuo (Guangxi), Baihe (Beijing), Qingyuan (Guangdong), Zhaoqing (Guangdong)
T1116_desc:
Starting Position:
Keep your body in a standing Position with your back and waist straight, feet together, hands akimbo.

Action:
Lift one leg from the side to the top, keeping the knee straight, and pause briefly to slowly return to the Starting Position.

Tips:
The supporting legs should be straight and perpendicular to the ground, keeping the balance of the body and holding the handrails with both hands if necessary.
T1094_desc:
Starting Position:
Lie on your back on the mat with your knees bent and your feet together. Place the ball on your chest and hold it with your hands.

Action:
Using explosive force, push the ball up as hard as you can along the elbow.When the ball falls, catch it with both hands.

Tips:
More suitable for individual training.
T1317_desc:
-Starting position:
Side lying position. The side of the body and one leg are in contact with the floor, ensuring stability of the body through the support point. Bend the knee. Place an elastic band around the knee area.

-Action:
Maintain pelvic stability. Using the hip as an axis, the knee of the upper leg opens upwards and both knees move away from each other overcoming resistance. Open to the maximum extent and then slowly return to the initial position. Keep the feet and hips still during the opening of the legs.

Tips:
Inhale when the legs are open and exhale when the legs are closed.
Stop training if you experience discomfort.
Adjust the amount of resistance according to the elasticity of different elastic bands, you can remove the elastic bands to train unloaded.
T1392_desc:
-Starting Position:
Feet apart, shoulder-width apart or slightly narrower, back straight, core tight. Raise the weight above your shoulders with one hand, while the other hand grips the weight naturally down the side of your torso.

-Action:
Slowly march forward in small steps.
Keep your back straight, shoulders open, shoulder blades down, head up, and spine in a neutral position as you move.

-Tips:
Stop the workout when you experience discomfort.
Tighten your core throughout to avoid body sway.
T1213_desc:
-Starting Position:
Begin in a standing position with arms hanging naturally and upper body straight.

-Action:
Lift one thigh with the calf perpendicular to the thigh, hooking the toes while lifting the opposite arm until the thigh is parallel to the floor. As you lift your leg the opposite foot does a pad step with the help of calf elasticity.
Extend the knee and press the foot down in front of you until the forefoot touches the ground. After touching the ground, tap the ground with the elasticity of the calf and then switch legs and hands to drive the body forward.

Tips:
Keep your core tight, keep your torso straight, and maintain torso stability.
Quickly leave the ground, reduce the time of touching the ground, ensure that the movement is fast and powerful, feel the elasticity of the lower limbs.
Pay attention to the coordination of hands and feet.
Touch the ground with the forefoot.
T1191_desc:
Starting Position:
Hold the half squat position, stand with the body side elastic band, pull the elastic band to the body position with both hands, and fix the elastic band.

Action:
Move the legs laterally in small steps, stretch the elastic band slowly, and repeat until recommended times.

Tip:
Keep your arms straight, your torso steady, your breathing balanced, and your movements smooth.

Practical Application:
In moving march, the control core is close to the core control in actual running.
T1295_desc:
-Starting Position:
Stand with your feet wide apart, toes facing diagonally forward.
Keep your back naturally straight and tuck in your stomach and chest. Arms are clasped in front of the chest or stretched straight forward to maintain balance.

-Action:
Squat down, bending your knees and hips, with your knees oriented in line with your toes.
Squat down until your thighs are parallel to the floor and slowly return to the starting position.

-Cue:
Inhale as you squat and exhale as you rise.
Stop the workout if you experience discomfort.
Tighten your core the entire time to avoid swaying your body.
You can carry a barbell on your back or hold a dumbbell kettlebell for weight training.
T1344_desc:
-Starting position:
Ball face down.
Stand on a platform and balance by supporting your body on one leg with a slight bend in the knee, leaning your upper body forward parallel to the ground and straightening the other leg back.

-Action:
Lift your torso up with all your might while straightening your supporting leg, swinging your back leg forward and returning to a standing position. After a short pause slowly return to the original position and repeat the movement until the recommended number of repetitions.
Coordinate your core, hips and lower body muscles to maintain balance and minimize swaying.

Tip:
You can reduce the difficulty of the movement by turning the ball face up.
Exhale on the way up and inhale on the way down.
H1057: Start exercising to record your activity data
H1058: Please import your recent activity data.
T1164_desc:
Starting Position:
Stand still with one leg resting on a bench in the back.

Action:
Bend your upright legs and knees so that your body sinks until your knees are bent to 90°. Pause briefly and use your leg strength to recover.

Tip:
In the process of the leg squat can be appropriately increased weight, improve the training effect.
T1078_desc:
Starting Position:
Maintain a squat Position with your back straight, your thighs parallel to the floor, your hands at rest according to your habit, and tighten your hips.

Action:
Use the strength of the lower limbs to bounce, at the same time the body in the air, landing is to restore the Starting Position, a short stay can start the second bounce.

Tips:
Keep your back and waist straight at all times and your thighs parallel to the ground when you land.
T1319_desc:
-Starting Position:
Kneeling position with hips near heels. The elastic band is secured at a height near the hip on one side and the other is placed over the hip to maintain some tension.

-Action:
Push your hips forward and lift your hips until your thighs are in line with your torso. Sit backward and return to the starting position.

-Cue:
Exhale as you lift your hips and inhale as you return.
Stop training when you experience discomfort.
Adjust the amount of resistance according to the elasticity of different elastic bands.
T1279_desc:
-Starting Position:
Feet apart, shoulder-width apart, lean forward slightly, knees slightly bent, keep your body stable.
Lean forward, torso as parallel to the ground as possible, arms naturally hanging down, palms facing each other, thumbs forward.

-Action:
Raise your arms to the sides, pause briefly after your arms are parallel to the ground, and put your arms in a T-shape with your body.
Slowly return to the starting position.

-Tips:
Exhale as you lift and inhale as you lower.
Stop the exercise if you experience discomfort.
T1099_desc:
Starting Position:
Stand on one side of the ball and place the ball flat up with your feet shoulder-width apart.Keep your waist and back straight with your head facing straight ahead.

Action:
Bend your knees and hips and lower your body, keeping your knees, feet and hips together.Squat as deep as your flexibility allows.Don't sag your knees and don't bend your thoracic vertebra.After a short pause in the Position where the squat is not possible, extend your knees and hips and return to the Starting Position.

Tips:
During the practice, it is important to master the balance of the wave ball, and the overall movement is similar to the squat.
T1261_desc:
-Starting Position:
With your hands on the ground, touch your thumbs and forefingers to each other to form a diamond-like lozenge shape. Head, torso and legs in a straight line.

-Action:
Keeping your body stable, slowly bend your elbows to lower your body, keeping your elbows close to your body. Pause briefly when the upper arm is nearly parallel to the ground. Push your body upward to return to the starting position.
When performing the movement, always keep your core muscles tight and your back straight, do not collapse or pucker your hips. Keep your neck naturally extended and don't tilt your head up or down excessively.

-Tip:
Inhale as you descend and exhale as you push up.
Stop training when experiencing discomfort.
Adjust the range of descent according to flexibility and personal ability.
T1092_desc:
Starting Position:
Lie flat on the mat with your legs bent at 90 degrees and your feet on a Swiss ball.Hold your hands at the sides of your head, elbows out.

Action:
Keeping your lower back on the ground, use your lower belly to lift your shoulders and exhale.Until the abdominal muscles contract to the limit.After a brief pause, return slowly to the Starting Position, inhaling.

Tips:
Do not use the strength of other parts of the exercise process, only with the strength of the waist and abdomen.
T1196_desc:
Starting Position:
Keep your upper body straight, extend your left arm in front of you and grip the elastic band, and drop your other arm behind you.Bend your right knee, keep your left leg on your knees, and take a lunge position.

Action:
Pull the elastic band to one side of the body while keeping the upper body straight and slightly tilted back;The arms swing back and forth naturally;At the same time, lunge with your legs straight and kneel with your knees raised.Return to original condition after a short stay and repeat until recommended times.

Tip:
The hands and feet work together, lifting the knee on the tiptoe and exerting steady control at the high point.

Practical Application:
Strengthen the integration of lower limbs and diagonal of the body, which is conducive to improving running efficiency.
T1268_desc:
-Starting Position:
Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, keeping your spine naturally straight and your core tight.

-Action:
Cross one leg in front of the other, with the hand on the same side of the front leg crossed and the opposite hand raised to point to the sky.
Tilt your torso in the direction of the crossed hand and feel the stretch in your outer thigh.
T1202_desc: Please follow your training program for 4-finger hang or 3-finger hang. We generally don’t recommend 2-finger hang unless you have specific training goals, to prevent injury. The same rule applies to the depth of the hold as well.
T1143_desc:
Starting Position:
Lie on your side and keep your body straight with only your lower arms and feet touching the ground.

Action:
Bring your far leg and arm up simultaneously to a running position and breifly hold until returning to the starting position.  

Tip:
Improve the quality of your movements by keeping your body balanced during practice.
T1046_desc:
Starting Position:
Keep your stance under the gantry, and adjust your two griphors to be on either side of the gantry and pull one with each hand.

Action:
Use the strength of the shoulder and the big arm to pull the ring up slowly until the arm is straight.

Tips:
Both arms require simultaneous power, the footwall stable good center of gravity.
T1130_desc:
Starting Position:
Maintain a standing position.

Action:
Try and quickly kick your butt with your heel as your calf comes up. Push your body forward with the supporting leg. 

Tip:
Maintain your balance and pace during workout.
T1019_desc:
Starting Position:
Bend forward, grab the barbell with both hands, and slowly lift to regain your standing Position.

Action:
Lift the barbell slowly until it reaches the lower bar height, pause briefly, then resume the Starting Position.

Tips:
Keep your body straight and your speed steady with your arms close to your side.
T1333_desc:
-Starting Position:
Hold the bar squarely in both hands with a grip slightly wider than shoulder width and palms facing forward. The body hangs naturally, the feet may be crossed or bent at the knees, and the core is tightened to avoid body sway.

-Action:
Keeping your elbows unbent, contract the muscles in your upper back and pull your shoulder blades downward. Move up a short distance and pause at the highest point.

-Tip:
Exhale as you pull up and inhale as you lower down.
S1006: 城西大学男子駅伝部低酸素トレーニング

S1002: 喜欢训练 x 高驰动态体验课

T1215_desc:
-Starting Position:
Kneel with your hips sitting on your heels.

-Action:
Lie forward with your arms shoulder-width apart and press your body and down as far as you can, feeling the stretch in your upper back.
Hold at maximum extent for a while.

-Tips:
Don't hold your breath, keep your breathing rhythm.
Stop training if you experience discomfort.
P10570: 30 min Aerobic/Low Intensity Run with Pick Ups
T1137_desc:
Starting Position:
Start in a lunge position. The lower knee should be slightly off the ground.

Action:
Take a controlled step forward and bend your knee to 90-degree angles and slowly bring yourself back up after a short pause. Alternate feet between repetitions.

Tips:
Keep your back straight throughout.
T1338_desc:
-Starting Position:
Sit in a seated position, maintaining postural stability through contact of the feet, hips, and back with the apparatus. Bend the elbows, angle the upper arms to the body about 60°, and hold the handles of the apparatus with both hands.

-Action:
With chest and triple hair force, extend the elbows to push the handles forward. Pause briefly after straightening the arms.
Chest and triple hair force to control speed and slowly return to the starting position.

Tip:
Exhale as you push forward and exhale as you return.
Keeping the upper arm at an angle to the torso reduces stress on the shoulder joint.
Stop training if you feel discomfort during the movement.
T1073_desc:
Starting Position:
Lie flat on your back in your gym chair and place the bell piece on your forehead.The shoulders should be slightly over the chair and the head should be completely over the chair.

Action:
Place the bell piece firmly on your forehead and slowly lean back in a semicircle while inhaling.Lift your head, return to the Starting Position by half circle, and exhale.Hold the contracting Position for a short time.

Tips:
Keep the rhythm step by step, do not force too hard, weight should not be too high.
T1169_desc:
Starting Position:
Keep your stance on the treadmill.

Action:
Turn on the treadmill, adjust your running speed and slope to suit you, and walk at a set pace until the recommended time.

Tip:
Pay attention to adjust the speed and slope of the treadmill.
T1242_desc:
-Starting Position:
Use your fingertips to brace yourself on the ground with your hands shoulder-width apart or slightly wider than shoulder-width apart. Head, torso and legs in a straight line.

-Action:
Keeping your body stable, slowly bend your elbows to lower your body, keeping your elbows close to your body. Pause briefly when the upper arm is nearly parallel to the ground. Push your body upward to return to the starting position.
When performing the movement, always keep your core muscles tight and your back straight, do not collapse or pucker your hips. Keep your neck naturally extended and don't tilt your head up or down excessively.

-Tip:
Inhale as you descend and exhale as you push up.
Stop training when experiencing discomfort.
Adjust the range of descent according to flexibility and personal ability.
T1006_desc:
Starting Position:
Lie down on the bench, knees at 90 degree angles, feet stabilized by the foot pads and place your hands behind your ears.

Action:
Roll your upper body up until your elbows touch your knees (or close to it) and lower yourself back down after a short pause.

Tips:
To avoid pulling your neck with your hands, look straight up instead of looking at your knees.
T1177_desc:
Starting Position:
Stand above the kettlebell with your feet shoulder-width apart.

Action:
Gradually bend your knees slightly and let your right hand drop until you reach the kettlebell handle.Grab the kettlebell with one hand and swing it up between the legs. As the kettlebell swings, the hip legs exert strength, the knees are straight, the roots of the feet hit the ground, tighten the core, and squeeze the hips.As the kettlebell swings downwards, it gradually returns to its original shape.Repeat to recommended times.

Tip:
Pay attention to the rhythm of the exercise, beginners can start with a light weight kettlebell.
T1065_desc:
Starting Position:
Lie down on the bench, hold the weight with your knees close to 90 degree angles and grab the provided handles with both hands.

Action:
Push the weight stack by extending your legs and let it slowly swing back after a short pause.

Tips:
Breathe out when pushing out and breathe in when letting the weight stack swing back.
T1038_desc:
Starting Position:
Sit on the bench with your hands behind your hips, palms down.

Action:
Use lumbar abdomen force to bend knee, at the same time double leg merges raise till heel is close to hip, after stopping for a short time slow restore original state, during both feet cannot touch the ground.

Tips:
Keep your balance and work slowly and efficiently.
T1274_desc:
-Starting Position:
Body upright, take a big step forward with one foot on one side. Bend the front side leg at the knee with the thigh parallel to the floor. Rear side leg extended. Maintain balance with both hands.

-Action:
Lower your hips to stretch your lower leg muscles.

-Tip:
Stop training if you experience discomfort.
T1033_desc:
Starting Position:
Lie on the floor, knees at 90 degree angles and place your hands flat on the floor, arms extended.

Action:
Raise your buttocks from the floor as high as you comfortably can and lower it back down after a short pause.

Tips:
Your feet and hands should not move throughout.
T1234_desc:
-Starting Position:
Hands and knees on the floor in a four-point support position. Hands are shoulder-width apart, knees are hip-width apart, back remains flat, and abdomen is tightened.

-Actions:
Cow Pose: As you inhale, tilt your pelvis forward, tilt your tailbone up, and extend your lumbar, thoracic, and cervical vertebrae section by section, forming a concave arc of the back.
Cat Pose: Look up to the front or above, chest open, shoulder blades inward, abdomen slightly stretched but core control maintained.
As you exhale, roll backward from the pelvis, arching the lumbar, thoracic, and cervical vertebrae section by section, the back rises like a cat arching its back.
Look down to the abdomen, which tucks in, core activates, and hips tighten slightly.

-Tip:
Move the entire spine and fully extend the low back in a controlled manner.
T1103_desc:
Starting Position:
Secure the elastic band around the lower leg.Its Position as close as possible to the knee Position is relatively easy, the more down is more difficult, maintain the elastic belt Position is fixed, the body is in a standing posture, knees and buttocks slightly bent, two feet open and shoulder width, head and chest, keep the back and waist straight.

Action:
Lower your weight and take a slow step sideways.Tip your toes forward and keep your weight low.Once you've done this, do the same with the other leg.Slowly step out of the side and tighten the elastic band.Keep your feet shoulder-width apart and maintain tension.

Tips:
Move slowly and rhythmically, keeping upper body straight.
T1282_desc:
-Starting Position:
Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart or slightly wider than shoulder-width apart and your toes facing slightly diagonally forward. Raise both arms and hold a barbell above the anterior deltoid fascia, crossing your arms and gripping the barbell.
Keep your back naturally straight and tuck your stomach and chest.

-Action:
Squat down, bending your knees and hips, with your knees oriented in line with your toes.
Squat down until thighs are nearly parallel to the floor, pausing briefly.
Stomp and extend the lower leg to return to the starting position.

-Cue:
Inhale as you squat and exhale as you rise.
Stop training when you experience discomfort.
Tighten your core throughout, keeping your back straight and maintaining body stability.
T1312_desc:
-Starting Position:
Feet apart, shoulder-width apart, knees slightly bent. Hold the ends of the dumbbells with both hands and hug them in front of your chest. Keep your back straight, tuck in your stomach and lift your chest, and distribute your body weight evenly over your feet.

-Action:
Slowly bend forward on the axis of your hips. Keep your back straight during the lean. At the same time, push your hips back until your torso is nearly parallel to the floor. Push your hips forward and return to the starting position.

-Tip:
Inhale on the dip and exhale on the return.
Determine the range of motion based on flexibility and stop training when you experience discomfort.
T1247_desc:
-Starting Position:
Stand with your feet front and back apart.
Raise one arm against a wall with the upper arm parallel to the floor and the lower arm perpendicular to the floor.

-Action:
Turn your torso and feel the stretch in your chest.

-Tip:
Don't hold your breath and maintain a breathing rhythm.
Stop training if you experience discomfort.
T1365_desc:
-Starting Position:
Secure your ankles, either with a barbell, Nordic jerk device, or look for a helper.
Kneel on both knees, thighs perpendicular to torso and floor, arms crossed or clasped in front of chest, core tight.

-Action:
Lean your body forward, with the back of your thighs firing to control the speed of your body's movement. Slowly bring the chest closer to the floor. Ensure that your shoulders, hips, and knees are in a straight line during the movement and do not bend at the hips.
When the body reaches the bottom, you can power back up with the back of your thighs to return to the starting position, or you can use your hands to support yourself.

Tips:
Inhale as you lower your body and exhale as you return to the starting position.
Stop training when you experience discomfort.
You can use an elastic band to hang back to reduce the difficulty of the movement.
P11962: Easy Run w/ Short Hill Sprints
P11963: Easy Run w/ Short Hill Sprints
T1207_desc:
Starting point:
In a sitting position with your feet on the pedals, grasp the handles on the pullies of the rowing machine and slightly arch your back until you feel a small tension or clear stretch in the back muscles. Keep your knees slightly bent while avoiding locking your back out.
 
Action:
Straighten your arms and keep your body fixed. Hold the handle and pull back until the handle is close to the abdomen. You should feel the tightening of the back muscles, pause for 1 second, and then slowly resume the movement.
 
Tip:
Exhale during your pull and inhale when returning the handles.
T1325_desc:
-Starting Position:
Lie down on a bench or on the floor. One side of the elastic band is secured at the same height and the other side is hooked around the ankles of both legs.
Legs are opened shoulder-width apart, knees are slightly bent, and the elastic band is kept under some tension.

-Action:
Power up the back of your thighs and quickly bend your knees. Once you reach maximum amplitude, slowly return to the starting position.

-Tips:
Exhale as you bend the knee and inhale as you return.
Stop the exercise if you experience discomfort.
Adjust the resistance according to the elasticity of different elastic bands.
Exercises can be performed on one leg.
T1129_desc:
Starting Position:
Maintain a standing position.

Action:
Lift up your left knee to your chest. Switch to lift your right knee to your chest. Continue the movement, alternating legs and moving at a sprinting pace.

Tip:
Consistent rhythym in tune with consistent breathing will help to mazimize the effect of this exercise.
T1060_desc:
Starting Position:
Keep the upper body upright and step on the steps about 20cm high.

Action:
Quickly step up the steps and jump up, then switch legs on the way down.Want to rise up, the body is upright, the minimum support time.

Tips:
Can carry on the bare hand or the negative light apparatus training.
T1378_desc:
-Starting Position:
Stand with feet shoulder width apart. Grip distance is chosen based on shoulder mobility, and can be increased for less mobility. Arms are straight and hanging down naturally, with the straight stick in front of the body.

-Action:
Keeping your arms straight, slowly lift the straight stick upward from the front of your body, then using your shoulders as an axis, your arms drive the straight stick backward around until it reaches its maximum amplitude.
Once you reach the lowest point, wrap your arms forward to return to the starting position.

Tips:
Inhale as you circle backward and exhale as you circle forward.
Stop the exercise if you experience discomfort.
Keep your arms straight and all other body parts stable during the movement to avoid swaying or rotating.

T1221_desc:
-Starting Position:
Kneel with your torso in a straight line with your thighs and your knees open to shoulder width. Hands are clasped to the chest or hang naturally.

-Action:
Using the knee as an axis, tilt the thighs and torso back, tightening the core to ensure that the area above the knee is in a straight line. The front of the thigh generates force to control the speed of the backward tilt until it is at its maximum amplitude. Active force from the front thighs pulls the body slowly back to the starting position.

Tips:
The amplitude of the movement depends on the flexibility of the individual, control the amplitude to avoid strains.
Inhale when you lean back and exhale when you return.
T1343_desc:
-Starting Position:
Ball face down.
Lower limbs are in a reverse lunge position. The front foot is placed in the center of the platform above the bosu ball with the opposite hand in front.
Tighten the core and straighten the torso.

-Action:
Register and extend the knee and hip of the front side leg to bring the body upright. Simultaneously lift the knee of the back side leg up
until the thigh is slightly above horizontal.
Coordinate your core, hips and lower body muscles to maintain balance and minimize swaying during the movement.

Tip:
Assist the movement by swinging your arms.
Repeat the same side of the leg as one set several times, or alternate bilaterally.
The difficulty of the movement can be reduced by turning the ball face up.
Exhale on the way up and inhale on the way down.
T1002_desc:
Starting Position:
Grab the rail with both hands in a wide Position, palms facing forward.

Action:
Pull yourself up with both hands until your chin reaches just above the rail and lower yourself back down after a short pause.

Tips:
Breathe out while raising yourself and breathe in while lowering yourself back.
T1246_desc:
-Starting Position:
Stand with feet front and back apart, front leg bent at the knee, back leg straight, heels as close to the ground as possible.

-Action:
Lower your hips and feel the tugging sensation on the back of the rear calf of your back leg.
You can hook the toes of your back foot or raise your hands upward to further stretch the back of your calf.

-Tip:
Don't hold your breath and maintain a breathing rhythm.
Stop training if you experience discomfort.
T1149_desc:
Starting Position:
Keep your back position on the mat with your legs together, knees bent, hands flat at your sides.

Action:
While engaging your core slowly lift your upper body elevating both the upper and lower vertebrae from the floor until everything superior to the buttocks is not touching the ground

Tip:
During the exercise focus on engaging your core through the entire motion.
T1027_desc:
Starting Position:
Lie down on your back with your knees bent and feet planted on the floor. Hold a E-Z Barwith your arms reaching toward the ceiling at shoulder height. 

Action:
Slowly bend at the elbows to bring th weight down to above your forehead. Pause, then, slowly bring the weights back overhead. 

Tips:
Keep your upper arms still throughout.
T1375_desc:
-Starting Position:
Open your feet shoulder-width or slightly wider.
Keep your body slightly leaning forward, sit your hips back and keep your back straight.
Hold one end of the battle rope in each hand with your arms hanging down naturally.

-Action:
Simultaneously use both hands to generate power, bending your arms until the battle rope swings from side to side parallel to the ground, creating a continuous wave shape.
The power comes from the coordinated movement of the entire body, not just the wrist swing.
Strive to synchronize the waves to reach the other end of the battle rope.

-Tip:
Engage core throughout to stabilize the body, preventing swaying with rope movement.
Drive power through entire arms - avoid isolated wrist motion.
Select rope weight and oscillation speed according to individual capability.
Maintain rhythmic breathing patterns with controlled exhalation during exertion.
P12119:
Half marathon ability test
Test purpose:
By testing the results, the individual's pace model (score prediction, lactate threshold) is corrected to provide accurate reference for the pace interval of subsequent training.
Test suggestion:
1. Master a good running rhythm and make strategic arrangements in segments.
2, adequate rest, suitable testing environment and supply preparation.
3. If you feel unwell, please make adjustments according to the actual situation. Safety first.
P12116:
Arrange 5-10 minutes of warm-up by yourself. If completed in advance, you can skip it by pressing the "circle" button. For warm-up, it is recommended to jog, do joint exercises, and stretch muscles
Formal training is used as a reference for threshold pace intervals. The interval is set in the aerobic endurance zone, and the overall intensity is relatively easy. If there is a large deviation in the threshold pace of the personal data model, it will be difficult to execute. It is recommended to refer to the sensory state during execution and execute with a "relaxed" feeling.
After finding the appropriate rhythm during the process, try to train the stability of the pace as much as possible.
After an easy run, four sets of 15-second acceleration runs were arranged (do not go all out, run fast with acceleration).
T1192_desc:
Starting Position:
Maintain a push-up preparation position with a straight upper body.

Action:
Stretch and hold the elastic band with one arm, adjust the position of feet and supporting arm appropriately, so that the body continues to maintain the push-up posture.Pull down the arm holding the elastic band.Switch sides and continue until recommended times.

Tip:
Exhale and pull down, keeping 1-2S steady at the end of the action.Keep your torso level like steel plates and don't collapse.

Practical Application:
The three-point support plate is already a difficult movement. Combined with the elastic band resistance, the recruitment of core muscle groups is again improved, and active muscle control + passive weight load enable us to experience a different dynamic plate.

T1350_desc:
-Starting Position:
Sitting on a stool or kneeling on one leg, keep your back straight, tighten your abdominals, lift your chest and head up, and lean your body back slightly at an angle of about 30°-45° from the floor to stabilize your body and provide support for the movement. Hold the rope handle in one hand with the arm straight and the handle on the side of the head with the palm facing inwards.

-Action:
With your back firing, drive your arm to pull the rope down along the side of your body, imagining touching your elbow to your waist, keeping your elbow stable during the pull down and not overly abducted or adducted.
Pull the handle down to shoulder height, and after a brief pause at the lowest point, slowly and in a controlled manner, extend the arm upward to return to the starting position.

-Tip:
Exhale on the pull down and inhale on the return.
The trunk needs to be stable while performing unilateral exercises to reduce the risk of injury.
Choose the right weight.
T1214_desc:
-Starting Position:
Begin in a standing position with arms hanging naturally and upper body straight.

-Action:
Lift one thigh with the calf perpendicular to the thigh, hooking the toes while lifting the opposite arm until the thigh is parallel to the floor. As you lift your leg the opposite foot does a pad step with the help of calf elasticity.
The active foot presses down right under the ball of the foot until the forefoot touches the ground. After touching the ground the opposite foot pads while lifting the thigh to the outside of the body with the calf perpendicular to the thigh until the thigh is parallel to the ground and then presses down on the ball of the foot.
Tap the ground after the forefoot touches the ground, and switch legs and hands to drive the body forward.

Tips:
Keep your core tight, ensure your torso is straight, and maintain torso stability.
Get off the ground quickly, reduce the time of touching the ground, make sure the movement is fast and powerful, and feel the elasticity of the lower limbs.
Pay attention to the coordination of hands and feet.
Touch the ground with the forefoot.

T1131_desc:
Starting Position:
Maintain a standing posture and prepare yourself for running

Action:
Run forward with short stride at a fast pace and swing arms accordingly.

Tip:
Maintain the fast pace longer for better training result.
T1156_desc:
Starting Position:
Keep your legs together and your arms open in line with your shoulders.

Action:
Use your waist and abdomen to lift your legs high and swing alternately to the sides. Use your hands to keep your balance and swing to the recommended number of times.

Tip:
In the exercise process, pay attention to the body parts of the power, do not rely on the strength outside the waist and abdomen, exercise to maintain the rhythm, to avoid injury.
T1239_desc:
-Starting Position:
Elbows are located directly below the shoulders, with the lower arms parallel to the shoulders. Feet are spread apart, shoulder-width apart. Core tightens to ensure that the head, torso and legs are in a straight line.

-Action:
Turn your body to the side while opening the arm on the same side to point directly overhead. Core tightens to keep head, torso and legs in a straight line.

-Tip:
Exhale as you rotate and inhale as you return.
This movement is used to improve core stability, so it is important to coordinate the force through the lower back and hips to prevent the body from twisting or wobbling as you train.
You can alternate rotations or train on one side only.
T1285_desc:
-Starting Position:
Open your feet shoulder-width apart with your toes facing slightly outward.
Squat down and hold the barbell using a positive grip. Grip your hands slightly wider than shoulder-width apart, with your elbows straight and on the outside of your knees.
Keep your back straight, chest open, head in line with your torso, shoulders above the barbell, and eyes forward.

-Action:
First Pull-Up:
Strongly extend hips and knees, lift the barbell
Keeping the angle of the torso to the floor constant, the barbell bar is pulled upward near the calves.
TRANSITION:
Barbell is pulled to knee height, hips forward, knees slightly bent, thighs over barbell, knees under barbell.
Second Pull-Up:
Quickly extend the hip, knee, and ankle joints with the barbell close to the body.
As the lower leg joints approach full extension, quickly shrug your shoulders upward.
As the shoulders reach their highest position, bend the elbows and continue to pull the barbell upward.
Catch the bar:
Once the barbell reaches its highest point, flip your arms underneath the barbell while bending your knees to a quarter squat position.
Raise your upper arms up as high as you can, close to parallel to the floor. Catch the barbell using the anterior deltoid fascia. Keep your torso straight as you catch the bar.
Once the barbell is stabilized, stand up straight.
Lower:
Lower your elbows, lower the barbell to your thighs, bend your hips and knees, and slowly lower the barbell back to the floor.

Tip:
The movement requires continuous, uninterrupted, explosive force to pull the barbell up through the stirrups and extensions.
The movement is difficult, it is recommended to practice with lighter weights, and gradually increase the weight after the movement is skillful.
T1160_desc:
Starting Position:
Hold your back and use the strength of your arms and legs to lift your body and keep it arched.

Action:
Lift your legs above your head using the strength of your lower back and abdomen, hold the position slightly and slowly return to your original position.

Tip:
Pay attention to the process of restoring the original should use abdominal strength to slow the body down.
T1066_desc:
Starting Position:
Sit down on the bench and Position your ankles against the foot pads.

Action:
Raise your feet by extending your legs and slowly lower them back down slowly after a pause.

Tips:
Keep your back straight throughout.
T1163_desc:
-Starting Position:
Lie on your side with a kettlebell in your near-ground side hand and bent knee.

-Action:
Rotate the body into a supine position and raise the kettlebell upward with one hand, with the same side leg bent at the knee and on the floor; the other hand is held in the same line as the shoulders using a side plank, with both eyes on the kettlebell.
Flat arm elbow support the upper body until the upper body is completely sitting up; switch to palms of the hands to support the ground to raise the body, hip elevation to a certain extent after straightening the leg folded to the back of the body and one-knee kneeling on the ground; the use of kneeling knee and foot power to support the body, the palms of the hands gradually leave the ground, the body to keep straight, folded leg calf adjusted to a comfortable position; legs until the stand up, a short stay in accordance with the reverse order of the restoration of the The same as before.

-Tips:
Pay attention to the balance of the body during the training process, always keep your eyes on the kettlebell, and keep your movements rhythmic and crisp to improve the quality of training.
P12109: An easy, conversational run that can be done outside or on the treadmill. Focus on keeping your heart rate within your Aerobic Endurance Zone. Make sure to include a dynamic warm-up prior to starting.
T1382_desc:
-Starting position:
Adjust the chair back angle to tilt back 15 to 30°. Sit in a seated position, maintaining postural stability through foot, hip, and back contact with the chair. Choose an appropriate grip distance with the small arms near perpendicular to the floor and the bar held with the palms facing forward. The height of the barbell bar is close to chin height.

-Action:
Power up to push the barbell bar upward. Pause briefly with arms straight.
Power up to control speed and slowly return to the starting position.

-Tip:
Exhale on the upward push and exhale on the return.
You can choose to train in a standing position, adjusting the height of the barbell bar, feet apart, shoulder-width apart, keeping your body stable and your upper body movement points consistent.
Stop training when you feel uncomfortable during the movement.

T1336_desc:
-Starting Position:
Sit in a seated position, maintaining postural stability through foot, hip, and chest contact with the apparatus. Arms are raised in front of you and both hands grip the handles of the apparatus.

-Actions:
Power the back of the shoulders, driving the handles outward. Pause briefly after reaching maximum amplitude.
Control your speed and slowly return to the starting position.

-Cue:
Exhale as you expand outward and exhale as you return.
Slightly flex the elbow to reduce stress on the elbow and analyze presses for injuries.
Stop training if you feel discomfort during the movement.
T1307_desc:
-Starting Position:
Feet apart, slightly wider than shoulder width, dumbbells placed between feet. Flex your hips, hips back, calves and floor near vertical, and hold the dumbbells in one hand. Keep your core tight and avoid collapsing your back.

Action:
Quickly stomp and extend your ankles, knees, and hips to straighten your body while pulling the dumbbells up. Pull the dumbbells up to shoulder height with an upward explosive force, then turn your elbows to rotate the dumbbells and lift them above your head.
Hold briefly, then slowly return to the starting position.

-Tip:
Inhale on the squat and exhale on the lift.
Stop the workout if you experience discomfort.
Ensure core stabilization, transfer the force upward from the lower body and lift the dumbbells with the help of stirrups and extensions, without active force from the upper body to push upward.
Other tools such as kettlebells can be used to provide weight.
T1278_desc:
-Starting Position:
Feet apart, shoulder-width apart, lean forward slightly, knees slightly bent, keep your body stable.
Lean forward, torso as parallel to the ground as possible, arms naturally hanging down, palms facing each other, thumbs forward.

-Action:
Raise and open your hands forward, pause briefly after your arms are in a straight line with your torso, and put your arms in a Y shape with your body.
Slowly return to the starting position.

-Tips:
Exhale as you lift and inhale as you lower.
Stop the exercise if you experience discomfort.
T1095_desc:
Starting Position:
Hold a medicine ball in both hands, half squat, knees bent, feet slightly wider than shoulders.Lean forward, hips back, back and waist straight, and place the pill in the crotch.

Action:
Stretch your hips forward and straighten your legs to stand up.Throw the ball as far back as possible from the front of the body through the top of the head.

Tips:
Single training can be carried out with your back to the wall.
T1117_desc:
Starting Position:
Place the barbell on the tip of the trapezius.Chest straight, back and waist straight, head straight ahead.Open your feet, hip width apart, and point your feet outward.

Action:
Bend your knees and lower your body, pushing your hips as far back as possible.Make sure your knees are in line with your feet.Keep your torso as upright as possible.Keep your back straight and continue to lower your body, keeping weight focused on the front of your heels.When the thighs touch the calves, move in the opposite direction, moving the barbell up.

Tips:
Pay attention to the reasonable control of the load during the training to avoid injury.
T1059_desc:
Starting Position:
Keep standing and hold the barbell down in front of your thighs, arms extended and palms facing back.

Action:
Raise the barbell by raising your shoulders straight up and lower it slowly back down after a short pause.

Tips:
Keep your arms extended throughout.
T1170_desc:
Starting Position:
Maintain a standing posture, arms naturally hang, upper body straight.

Action:
Run at a slow pace according to your situation.

Tip:
Adjust your breathing and rhythm and keep your body relaxed.
T1249_desc:
-Starting Position:
Stand side-by-side, side planks, eyes forward.
Lift one side foot forward, toes straight, while keeping your arms up to keep your body balanced.

-Actions:
The stepped out leg drops, driving the body forward, and the front foot lands on the ground and stands firm. Lift the back side leg back while opening both arms to the sides until the torso and back side leg are parallel to the ground. Pause briefly to maintain balance.
Return to standing position.

-Tip:
Coordinate the muscles of the legs and core to maintain balance and avoid large wobbles.
T1178_desc:
Starting Position:
Keep your front feet crouched directly above the kettlebell.

Action;
Squeeze the hips and legs, grab the kettlebell with both hands and swing it up between the legs. At the top of the kettlebell swing, extend the hip joint, lock the knee, root into the ground, tighten the core and squeeze the hips.

Tip:
Keep the rhythm of the exercise, keep your back straight and avoid shaking.
T1250_desc:
-Starting Position:
Lie on your back with your legs bent at the knees, arms crossed above your head and arms straight.

-Actions:
Abdominal force to lift the upper back off the ground, while turning the upper body to the side, and then pressing down on the outside of the thighs on that side with both hands, similar to the ""logging"" action.
After a short pause to return to the starting position, repeat on the other side, alternating between left and right to complete the required number of times.

-Tips:
Exhale when you turn around and inhale when you return.
You can hold a heavy object to increase the difficulty of the movement.
T1346_desc:
-Starting Position:
Lie on your back with the foot of your training leg on the Swiss ball and the other leg lifted at the knee. Using the shoulders, head and arms as a pivot point, the core and hips are used to lift the body so that the shoulders, hips and legs are in a straight line.

-Action:
Power the back of the thigh of the training leg and bend the knee to pull the Swiss ball toward the hip until the calf is perpendicular to the thigh. Keep the thigh in a straight line with the torso at all times during the training leg's knee flexion, with the other leg in the same position.
Slowly extend the knee back to the starting position.

Tip:
You can reduce the difficulty of the exercise by placing both legs on the Swiss ball at the same time.
Instead of a Swiss ball, a sliding disk can be used, with similar movements and results.
Exhale when you bend your knee and inhale when you extend it.
T1031_desc:
Starting Position:
In a sitting Position, hold the barbell with your wrists against your knees and palms facing up.

Action:
Bend your wrists to lift the barbell and lower it slowly after a brief pause.

Tips:
Always press your forearm against your thigh.
SQ1317: 4 sets of metrics can be selected at the same time for comparison
T1339_desc:
-Starting Position:
Select the height of the barbell bar based on your height. Place the barbell bar on the obliques, feet apart, slightly wider than shoulder width, positioned in front of the plane of the barbell bar, with your body slightly back.

-Action:
Squat down with your knees pointing in the direction of your toes. Squat down until thighs are parallel to the floor and then pause slightly.
Extend the hip and knee joints and slowly return to the starting position.

-Tip:
Inhale as you squat and exhale as you rise.
Tighten your core to prevent spinal injuries.
Stop training if you feel discomfort during the movement.
E30015: The export operation is too frequent. Please try again after 7 days from the last application.
SQ1310: your Threshold Heart Rate Zones Distribution
P12274: 30 min Aerobic/Low Intensity Run with Pick Ups
T1041_desc:
Starting Position:
Sit on the 45 degree bench Position and grasp the handles with your palms facing forward.

Action:
Push the handles forward and slightly upwards by straightening your arms and allow them to slowly return after a short pause.

Tips:
Breathe out while pushing forward and breathe in while returning to Starting Position.
E17005: Unable to sync the plan unless the whole team is on the same start date.
T1314_desc:
-Starting Position:
Feet apart, shoulder-width apart, hold dumbbells on either side of your shoulders with both hands, palms facing inward.

-Action:
Squat: Bend your hips and knees and squat at an even pace, keeping your knees in the same direction as your toes during the squat. Squat until thighs are parallel to the ground or slightly lower.
Upward Push:
Use the power of your legs and hips to quickly pedal up and push your body upward. As your body pushes upward, your arms should quickly push the dumbbells upward until your arms are straight and the dumbbells are above your head. Transfer the power from your legs to your hips and then through your spine to your upper body to provide a strong momentum for pushing the dumbbells up.

-Tip:
Keep your body balanced and stable.
Inhale as you squat and exhale as you push up.
Evenly descend to build strength and push up quickly to release it.
Leg stomps and arm pushes should be coordinated to form a coherent whole, making full use of the explosive power of each joint.
P12277: 35 min Aerobic/Low Intensity Run with Pick Ups
P12276: 30 min Aerobic/Low Intensity Run with Pick Ups
T1329_desc:
-Starting Position:
Hold the bar squarely in both hands with a grip slightly wider than shoulder width and palms facing forward. Let go of one hand and drop your body naturally; your feet can be crossed or bent at the knees and your core tightened to avoid body sway.

-Action:
Keeping your elbows unbent, contract the muscles in your upper back and pull your shoulder blades downward. Move up a short distance and pause at the highest point.

-Tip:
Exhale as you pull up and inhale as you lower down.
T1304_desc:
-Starting Position:
Lie on your back on an Incline Bench Press Bench, maintaining a stable position through your feet, hips, back, and head.
Keep your upper arms at an angle to your torso, in contact with the floor, and your forearms perpendicular to the floor, holding dumbbells in your hands.

-Action:
Chest power push the dumbbells upward until the arms are straight. Slowly return to the starting position.

-Tip:
Exhale as you push up and inhale as you return.
Stop the workout if you experience discomfort.
T1037_desc:
Starting Position:
Kneel in front of a high pulley with ropes.Grab the rope with both hands and pull down until your hands are on either side of your cheek.

Action:
Use the strength of your lower back to slowly pull the rope down until your elbow moves to the middle of your thigh, pause briefly, and slowly return to the Starting Position.

Tips:
Weight is added according to the actual situation, waist and abdomen hair force to improve the training effect.
T1256_desc:
-Starting Position:
Front and back legs in a half-kneeling position (front leg bent at about 90 degrees, back leg on the knee). Torso is straight, avoiding excessive forward or backward leaning at the waist.

-Action:
Rear side foot is slowly pulled towards the hip by the opposite hand, push the hips forward, feel the stretch in the front of the thigh, and keep the body balanced.

-Tip:
Don't hold your breath and maintain a breathing rhythm.
Stop training if you experience discomfort.
G4007: If this score is not your best recent score, please enter your score so that we can analyze your physical fitness more accurately.
T1188_desc:
Starting Position:
Maintain a standing position with your body straight.

Action:
Stand straight with your arms out in front. Pick one leg off the ground and cross it behind your other leg. Slowly lower your body to the ground, until your hips are in a normal squat position. Drive up through your standing leg and repeat on the other side.

Tip:
Pay attention to your balance. Keep your back straight as you rise and fall, moving slowly and effectively.
T1260_desc:
-Starting Position:
Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart and your hands hanging naturally.

-Action:
Use your ankle and calf muscles to quickly push your body off the ground, keeping your legs straight and avoiding bending your knees.
Jump with arms swinging naturally to increase jump height and speed.
Land forefoot-first and quickly transition to full feet, keeping the ankle joint stable.

-Tip:
Emphasize quick reaction and flexibility over jump height.
Land with knees slightly bent to cushion the landing to avoid injury.
T1017_desc:
Starting Position:
Stand with your feet apart, your back straight, your arms hanging at your sides, and your hands holding the dumbbells.

Action:
Lift the dumbbell to shoulder level, elbows slightly bent, and rest for 3-6 seconds to return to Starting Position.

Tips:
Keep your body still, with only the driving muscles in motion.
T1024_desc:
Starting Position:
Place your upper arms against the arm rests and grab the easy-curl-bar with your arms close to being fully extended.

Action:
Raise the easy-curl-bar up until your forearms are perpendicular to the floor and lower it back down after a short pause.

Tips:
Keep your back and upper arms still throughout.
T1185_desc:
Starting Position:
Lie on your side on a yoga mat with your elbows on the near side of your body, keeping your body straight.

Action:
Lie on your side with your hips high off the floor and prop your upper body up on your elbow. Hold for as long as directed. 

Tip:
Improve the quality of movement, do not shake the body.
T1253_desc:
-Starting Position:
Hands on the ground, slightly less than shoulder distance apart. Head, torso and legs in a straight line.

-Action:
Keeping your body stable, slowly bend your elbows to lower your body, keeping your elbows close to your body. Pause briefly when the upper arm is nearly parallel to the ground. Push your body upward to return to the starting position.
When performing the movement, always keep your core muscles tight and your back straight, do not collapse or pucker your hips. Keep your neck naturally extended and don't tilt your head up or down excessively.

-Tip:
Inhale as you descend and exhale as you push up.
Stop training when experiencing discomfort.
Adjust the range of descent according to flexibility and personal ability.
T1311_desc:
-Starting Position:
Hold the bar in both hands with a grip slightly wider than shoulder-width apart, with your body naturally hanging down, feet together, knees slightly bent, and dumbbells sandwiched between your feet.

-Actions:
Abdominal power drives thighs up, bending the knees in a smooth motion until maximum amplitude.
Slowly return to the starting position.

-Tip:
Stop the workout when you experience discomfort.
You can increase the difficulty of the movement by keeping the legs straight up.
T1321_desc:
-Starting Position:
Standing with your legs together, place elastic loops around your ankles. Cross your arms or hold on to a stable place and tighten your core to keep your body steady.

-Action:
Lift one leg to the side, keeping it straight, until it is at its maximum extension. Slowly return to the starting position.

-Tip:
Exhale as you lift your leg and inhale as you return.
Stop training if you experience discomfort.
Adjust the amount of resistance according to the elasticity of different elastic bands or you can fix the band at knee height.
T1243_desc:
-Starting Position:
Lie on your back on the mat with your arms straight up perpendicular to the floor, palms facing each other or fists clenched.
Bend knees and raise legs with thighs perpendicular to the floor, calves parallel to the floor, and knees directly above hips.

-Action:
Slowly lower the opposite arm and leg, with the large arm close to the ear and the leg straightened out to the far side, both close to being parallel to the ground but not on the ground.
Core power drives the limbs back to the starting position.

-Tips:
Inhale as you lower and exhale as you return.
Control the movement to minimize swaying.
T1195_desc:
Starting Position:
Extend one arm forward and hold the elastic band tightly. Let the other arm drop naturally.Keep your knees bent and lower legs in a squat.

Action:
Pull the elastic band towards your body while keeping your upper body straight and slightly leaning back.Both arms swing back and forth naturally, lower limbs from squat movement into standing posture.Return to squat position after a short stay and repeat until recommended times.

Tip:
Squat movement, the center of gravity up and down, rise and fall to be full of flexibility.Maintain a certain rhythm of the movement to improve the training effect.

Practical Application:
Improve muscle strength in lower extremities and reduce the risk of running injuries.
T1263_desc:
-Starting Position:
Standing position, body straight, arms crossed for balance or holding on to a support point.

-Action:
Support the ground with one leg, keep the torso stable, straighten the other leg and swing from one side of the body to the other, try to keep the leg straight and swing evenly.

Tips:
Keep breathing during the swing.
Increase the amplitude of the swing as much as possible based on flexibility.
Keep your core tight and your torso stable to avoid swaying during the swing.
T1034_desc:
Starting Position:
Sitting on a leg lift, place your hips against the seat cushion and place your feet shoulder-width apart on the platform.Grab the handle and apply force from the heel to release the safety latch.

Action:
Inhale and slowly lower the load until the knees are 90 degrees.Pause for a moment, then push the weight strongly up through your heel to return to the Starting Position, then exhale as you push up through the midpoint of the action.

Tips:
Your knees should be slightly bent at the beginning of the movement and not fully extended during the lift.
T1141_desc:
Starting Position:
Lie flat on a yoga mat with your knees at a 90-degree Angle, both knees together and one knee not bent. Place your hands flat on the floor and your arms at your sides.

Action:
Raise your hips and hips as high as you can, while bending your straight knees as high as you can and lowering them slowly after a brief pause.Continue until recommended number of times.

Tips:
Pay attention to the power source and keep your balance.
T1198_desc:
Starting Position:
In a semi-squat position, bend your knees slightly, keep your arms straight, one of your arms holding the elastic band, and keep your upper body straight.

Action:
Press down your arms quickly and return to the original position. Pull the elastic band to one side of your body.The hip legs naturally fall and rise with the swing of the arms.Repeat to recommended times.

Tip:
To maintain a fast rhythm, exhale, bend and press the hips down.Adjust your feet and stabilize your center of gravity.

Practical Application:
Large range of motion, conducive to stimulating the heart and lung.Acceleration of hip flexion helps improve centrifugal control. For running touchdown and off-road downhill, buffer control can be greatly improved to reduce the risk of injury caused by impact.
T1044_desc:
Starting Position:
Lie down on your back on an incline bench and grab one dumbbell with each hand at shoulder height, elbows at 90 degree angles.

Action:
Raise the dumbbells until they are side by side on top of you and slowly lower them back after a short pause.

Tips:
Try to maintain the same angle in your elbows throughout.
T1107_desc:
Starting Position:
Maintain a standing posture with your back straight, feet shoulder-width apart and tramping on elastic rope, hands hanging naturally at your sides and gripping the elastic rope.

Action:
Keeping the elbow slightly bent, contract the deltoid and lift the arm to a horizontal Position. At the highest point, the shoulder is slightly higher than the elbow and the elbow is slightly higher than the wrist.

Tips:
Pay attention to the slow motion range, keep the waist and back straight at all times.
T1301_desc:
-Starting Position:
Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart or slightly wider than shoulder-width apart and your toes facing slightly diagonally forward.
Hold dumbbells or kettlebells in both hands and hug them to your chest, elbows close to your sides.
Keep your back naturally straight and tuck in your stomach and chest.

-Action:
Squat down, bending your knees and hips, with your knees oriented in the same direction as your toes.
Squat down until thighs are nearly parallel to the floor, pausing briefly.
Stomp and extend the lower leg to return to the starting position.

-Cue:
Inhale as you squat and exhale as you rise.
Stop training when you experience discomfort.
Tighten your core throughout, keeping your back straight and maintaining body stability.

T1182_desc:
Starting Position:
Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart.

Action：
Bend over, touch the ground in front of your feet with your hands, adjust your position and try not to bend your knees.Move your hands forward, keeping your knees straight and your upper body straight, until you are in a push-up ready position. Hold the position briefly and then move your body back and back into a standing position.Repeat to recommended times.

Tip:
Improve the quality of movement, keep the upper body and knees straight, do not move the feet.
T1229_desc:
-Starting Position:
Lie on your back with your legs bent, heels on the ground, and feet shoulder-width or slightly widerapart.

-Action:
Lift your hips slowly upward so that your body forms a straight line from your shoulders to your knees.
When the hips are lifted to the highest point, hold the position for some time.

-Tip:
Keep your feet steady on the ground to provide stable support for your body.
Focus your attention on glute power without active force from your hands and feet.
Tighten your core while keeping your breathing even and not holding your breath.
T1204_desc: Please follow your training program for 4-finger hang or 3-finger hang. We generally don’t recommend 2-finger hang unless you have specific training goals, to prevent injury. The same rule applies to the depth of the hold as well.

T1272_desc:
-Starting Position:
Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, keeping your spine naturally straight and your core tight.

-Action:
Take a small step forward with one foot on one side, hook your toes, straighten your leg, bend at the hip, and feel the stretch in the back of your leg by rowing your hands to the front foot while bending your back leg.
Rise back to a standing position and switch legs for the exercise.

-Tip:
You can practice this in place or alternate as you march.
Exhale as you bend down and inhale as you rise up.
Control the range of motion based on flexibility.
T1236_desc:
-Starting Position:
Stand in a standing position with hands hanging naturally.

-Actions:
Keep your knees straight and your toes up, emphasizing quick contact between the forefoot and the ground. Actively pick the ground backward to propel the body forward.
Keep your upper body straight, with your head, shoulders and hips in a straight line and your arms swinging naturally to assist with power.
Swing your arms in a strong and coordinated manner, with your elbows close to the sides of your body and a moderate swing.

Tips:
Reduce the contact time between your feet and the ground, complete the stomping and reaching movements quickly, and keep a brisk pace.
T1349_desc:
-Starting Position:
Place the Swiss ball in front of your body with both elbows resting on the Swiss ball and elbows directly under your shoulders. With your body in a plank position, tighten your core and make sure your body is in a straight line from head to toe.

-Action:
Control your body and the Swiss ball to remain stable for a certain amount of time.

-Tip:
Keep your breathing even and steady, don't hold your breath.
This movement is used to improve core stability, so it's important to coordinate your power through your lower back and hips to prevent your body from twisting or wobbling during the workout.
T1076_desc:
Starting Position:
Sit on the floor, lean back to rest on your forearms, bend your hips and extend one leg 45 degrees from the ground.

Action:
While you push one leg out until it is stretched forward, bring the other one back so that you are cycling through the air.

Tips:
Try to keep your back straight throughout.
T1051_desc:
Starting Position:
Grip both bars with your hands and lower yourself until your elbows are at 90 degree angles.

Action:
Lift yourself up by extending your arms until your elbows are close to locking and lower yourself back after a short pause.

Tips:
Breathe out while pushing yourself up and breathe in while lowering yourself down.
T1166_desc:
Starting Position:
Keep standing on the bench.

Action:
Lift one foot onto the bench, balance your legs, lift your body until your feet are together, then slowly return to your original position after a short pause. Repeat for the recommended number of times.

Tip:
Pay attention to the power position to improve the effectiveness of training.

T1211_desc:
-Starting Position:
Legs together, knees bent, leg lifted, torso and thighs in a V, upper hips supporting the ground, hands on knees

-Action:
Hands against knees, abdominal force to maintain position

-Tips:
Breathe naturally
Change the duration and the force to adjust the intensity
T1231_desc:
Lean your back against a wall and slowly squat down until your calves are perpendicular to the floor and your thighs are parallel to the floor. Maintain this position for some time.
Place your hands on your knees or hang down naturally.
T1114_desc:
Starting Position:
Wrap elastic tape around a post or other solid object.In a standing Position, the left side of your body is facing the column and the elastic band is wrapped around your right ankle.

Action:
Keeping the upper body straight, lift your right leg and knee straight and try to lift it as far away as possible.Then pause briefly and return to the Starting Position.

Tips:
It requires a certain rhythm and balance.
T1134_desc:
Starting Position:
Stand up and get your body ready to run.

Action:
Kick your body out, bend your other knee and lunge forward. When you land, lunge legs will continue to lunge your body forward. Repeat until the recommended number of times.The arm swings in rhythm.

Tip:
Pay attention to the power position and maintain the air position.

T1069_desc:
Starting Position:
Lean over the mat and keep the thighs in contact with the floor.

Action:
Use lower limb strength to fold crus as far as possible, heel is close to hip as far as possible, return to start Position slowly after brief stay.

Tips:
The rest of the body should remain stationary except for the movement of the calf.
T1173_desc:
-Starting Position:
Remain in a supine position on a downward sloping plank with the barbell plates resting on your chest in both hands.

-Actions:
Use your lower back and abdominal strength to lift your upper body, stop briefly to squeeze your abs and then slowly lower your upper body back to its original position, and repeat the movement for the recommended number of reps.

-Tip:
Pay attention to the rhythm of body movement control, barbell piece according to their own actual situation to choose.

T1265_desc:
-Starting Position:
Standing or seated, raise the stretching side arm above your head, bending the elbow, with the palm of the hand near the shoulder blade.

-Action:
With your other hand, pull the elbow of the stretching side toward the midline of your body and feel the three-head stretch.

-Tip:
Keep breathing normally.
Adjust the range according to flexibility to avoid overstretching.

T1356_desc:
-Starting Position:
Keep your feet open and shoulder-width apart to keep your body stable.
Raise your arms flat in front of you, slightly below your shoulders, making a small angle between your arms and your torso. Hold the rope handle on the opposite side with the ropes crossed. Keep your arms straight and at shoulder level.

-Action:
A force from the back of the shoulder drives the elbow backward, driving the arm backward and opening it up, keeping the angle of the elbow joint constant during the process.
Arms and body line up to reach maximum amplitude, pause briefly and slowly return to the starting position.

Tips:
Breathe
Exhale as you pull back and inhale as you return
Feel the force at the back of your shoulders.
T1180_desc:
Starting Position:
Holding a kettlebell while standing, hold it over your right shoulder while pushing it over the same shoulder.Feet shoulder-width apart.

Action;
The arms holding kettlebell remain still, and the body begins to lean to the other side until the waist is bent beyond bending, return to original shape after a short stay, repeat the action to the recommended number of times before changing sides.

Tip:
Pay attention to maintain the rhythm of this movement, to avoid lumbar movement injury.
T1127_desc:
Starting Position:
Maintain a standing posture and prepare yourself to run.

Action:
Run on the spot at a fast pace with your arms swinging naturally. 

Tip:
Maintain your balance during workout.
T1049_desc:
Starting Position:
Lie on your back on the bench with your palms on the back of the dumbbell, elbows bent and arms perpendicular to the floor.

Action:
Bend at the elbow and let the dumbbell sink gradually along with the palm toward the head until the arm is parallel to the ground. After a short pause, slowly lift the dumbbell until it returns to the Starting Position using the latissimus dorsius and pectoralis major muscles.

Tips:
Don't use too much weight and feel your back muscles stretch when you exercise.
T1355_desc:
-Starting Position:
Kneeling position with the pulley of the rope above the head, on the side of the body. The front side leg is close to the direction of the apparatus.
Hold the ends of the handles with both hands, arms straight, handles tilted, lower ends at shoulder height, palms angled down.

-Action:
With the core firing, the upper body rotates to the opposite side while the arms stroke in a diagonal direction along the body in an angled downward chopping motion.
After reaching maximum amplitude, the body and arms slowly return to the starting position on the original trajectory.

-Tip:
Exhale on the downward chop and inhale on the return.

T1388_desc:
